Genome Name: Campylobacter jejuni subsp. jejuni NCTC 11168 = ATCC 700819
Isolation Comments: isolated from a diarrheic patient in 1977 and minimally passaged
Comments: Campylobacter jejuni strain NCTC11168. This strain (originally 5636/77) was isolated from a diarrheic patient in 1977 and minimally passaged. This strain displays aberrant virulence phenotypes in animal models and tissue culture. Contains many homopolymeric tracts in the genome which result in hypervariable sequences in many genes having to do with cell surface structures. These sequences result in hypervarible antigenic diversity and immune evasion. Overall, the genome contains very few repetitive DNA sequences and very few coding regions arranged in operons. Pathogenicity factors include cytolethal-distending toxin, hemolysin-like toxins, and a type II secretion system.

Isolation Comments: isolated from humans have been subjected to both whole genome sequencing and to comparative proteomics using iTRAQ reagents
Comments: Four very different C. jejuni strains isolated from humans have been subjected to both whole genome sequencing and to comparative proteomics using iTRAQ reagents. The overall goal of the project is to determine the utility of the proteomics/mass spectrometry approach for characterizing and differentiating isolates in the context of known whole genome sequence data. It will be of critical importance to determine whether or not there are any artifacts or errors arising from the analysis of data when utilizing applications such as Scaffold and what the nature of these errors may be (eg. problems with data normalization due to the differential protein content of samples). These data will be useful for developing a more complete understanding of protein expression differences in different strains and of the differential gene content that may be responsible.

Isolation Source: the blood of a human patient who was having a renal transplant
Isolation Comments: isolated from the blood of a human patient who was having a renal transplant and is the best characterized isolate of this species
Comments: Campylobacter fetus subsp. fetus 82-40. This strain (82-40) was isolated from the blood of a human patient who was having a renal transplant and is the best characterized isolate of this species.. The ratio of bloodstream infection to diarrheal illnesses for C. fetus is nearly 400-fold higher than for C. jejuni, indicating its marked propensity for invasive disease compared to C. jejuni.

Isolation Comments: Isolated from the Red Cross Children's Hospital in Cape Town, South Africa, it is linked to the most common type of GBS, acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy (AIDP)
Comments: Campylobacter jejuni subsp. jejuni 260.94.This strain is a representative of the Campylobacter strains of the Penner o:41 serotype, which is associated with Guillain-Barre syndrome (GBS). Isolated from the Red Cross Children's Hospital in Cape Town, South Africa, it is linked to the most common type of GBS, acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy (AIDP).  This organism has been shown to express the GM1 ganglioside-like structure, and is a member of the second known overrepresented serotype associated with GBS.

Isolation Source: both the patient and from the poultry flock sampled at the abattoir, thus providing a clear-cut case of the direct transmission of disease from poultry to human
Isolation Comments: isolated the M1 strain (laboratory designation 99/308) from both the patient and from the poultry flock sampled at the abattoir, thus providing a clear-cut case of the direct transmission of disease from poultry to human
Comments: Campylobacter jejuni subsp. jejuni M1.Following a research visit to a poultry abattoir, one surveillance team member developed campylobacteriosis. We isolated the M1 strain (laboratory designation 99/308) from both the patient and from the poultry flock sampled at the abattoir, thus providing a clear-cut case of the direct transmission of disease from poultry to human. We have determined the genome sequence of the M1 strain and compared it to other previously published Campylobacter genomes. We found the M1 genome to contain many genes related to chicken colonization which are not ubiquitous in the published genomes. The M1 genome represents a confirmed pathogen and chicken colonizer useful for further comparative studies.
